sec.p:
Consider a generic self-replicating system, where different species are described in terms of an inherited strategy (or a trait) v belonging to a certain space V. In particular, v can be a function-valued trait. We assume that v belongs to a compact domain in a metric space V equipped with a Borel measure μ∗\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mu ^*$$\end{document}. (The measure is required to rigorously quantify sets of hereditary strategies).

The presence of each strategy v in the system at time t is characterised by a non-negative quality ρ(v,t)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\rho (v,t)$$\end{document} which is a continuous function of t and v. Thus, ρ(v,t)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\rho (v,t)$$\end{document} is a function on the space V integrable with respect to measure μ∗\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mu ^*$$\end{document}. In the case where the strategy v is absent, we have ρ(v,t)≡0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
