(Ranking order) We state v≻w\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$v\succ w$$\end{document}, that is, strategy v is more advantageous, or fitter, than strategy w if the ratio between the densities tends to zero uniformly in some vicinities O(v) and O(w) of v and w, i.e.2limt→∞ρ(w′,t)ρ(v′,t)=0,∀v′∈O(v),w′∈O(w).\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \lim _{t\rightarrow \infty }\frac{\rho (w',t)}{\rho (v',t)}=0, \forall v'\in O(v), w'\in O(w). \end{aligned}$$\end{document}

For fixed initial conditions, Definition 1 establishes a partial ranking order in the space V; in other words, the introduced relation satisfies axioms of transitivity (from v≻w\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$v\succ w$$\end{document} and w≻u\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$w\succ u$$\end{document} it follows that v≻u\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$v\succ u$$\end{document}) and anti-reflexivity (an element cannot be better than itself). We should stress that the above-introduced order is a partial one, i.e. for some elements the limit in expression (2) can be a positive number; in this case, both strategies may coexist or may both go extinct. Note that here we focus on the scenario where the introduced ranking order does not depend on the initial condition. In this case, when randomly generating several strategies, the probability that some strategies show coexistence will be zero (for detail see next subsection). We also briefly consider a model study case where the ranking order can depend on the initial conditions (Sects. 2.3 and 4.2).

