				\begin{document}$$\overrightarrow{M}$$\end{document}, we simulate their joint long-term dynamics using (1). Then, we rank competing strategies based on their per capita growth rates, and then, using this ranking we approximate the location of the best point with the maximal fitness. Here, we assume that we do not have the situation where strategies coexist, i.e. to have strategies with equal fitness. This signifies that we do not have neutral evolution, where a set of points of equal fitness in the considered n-dimensional parametric space may have a nonzero measure. For example, for n=2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
